    {
      "id": "4ef1908dd0cdf08fe6eaeae026660a4c4205b812",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-14 07:19:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> What do you mean by indefinitely?  Won't it just wait for the next TXG?\n\nyes, it will, but if requested size (i.e. estimated size for TX) is too big, then it will get stuck till reboot.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "71305306f0b4a67c82adaa2535677b3dc0fba0d1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 747,
        "name": "Tony Hutter",
        "email": "hutter2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "hutter2",
        "status": "LLNL"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-16 01:09:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>>    What do you mean by indefinitely?  Won't it just wait for the next TXG?\n\n> yes, it will, but if requested size (i.e. estimated size for TX) is too big, then it will get stuck till reboot.\n\nSo is it getting stuck because we're using an invalid TXG size, or do you think there's a ZFS bug going on here? \n\nAlso, I see your loop will run like this:\n\nlimit=10: dmu_tx_assign(oh->ot_tx, TXG_NOWAIT);\nlimit=9: dmu_tx_assign(oh->ot_tx, TXG_WAITED);\nlimit=8: dmu_tx_assign(oh->ot_tx, TXG_WAITED);\n...\nlimit=1: dmu_tx_assign(oh->ot_tx, TXG_WAITED);\n\nMaybe I'm missing something, but how would this prevent dmu_tx_assign(TXG_WAITED) from getting stuck?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ab4ff0d165dd5f67db11f3a230c52347a6956bb7",
